         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1213">
               <p>Daughter of a merchant, <persName>Thomas Garrett</persName>, Dorothea married a
                  creditor named <persName>King</persName> to save her father from debtor&apos;s
                  prison. The marriage was cruel and unhappy, ending in separation. After her
                  conversion Dorothea became a class leader of great spiritual repute and one of the
                  legendary characters of early <placeName>Dublin</placeName> Methodism, as well as
                  one of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s
                  frequent correspondents. In <date when="1784">1784</date> she married the retired
                     <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg>
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1162.xml"/>John
                  Johnson</persName><!-- Unsure if this is the correct ID -->. See Crookshank, <hi
                     rend="italic">Ireland</hi>, 1:123, 384, 387; and Crookshank, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Irish Women</hi>, 53–62.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
